ğŸ‘‰Data visualization: The graphical representation of data

ğŸ‘‰Bar graph: A data visualization that uses size to contrast and compare two or more values

ğŸ‘‰Line graph: A data visualization that uses one or more lines to display shifts or changes in data
over time

ğŸ‘‰Pie chart: A data visualization that uses segments of a circle to represent the proportions of
each data category compared to the whole

ğŸ‘‰Map: A data visualization that organizes data geographically

ğŸ‘‰Histogram: A data visualization that shows how often data values fall into certain ranges

ğŸ‘‰Heat map: A data visualization that uses color contrast to compare categories in a dataset

ğŸ‘‰Correlation: The measure of the degree to which two variables change in relationship to each
other

ğŸ‘‰Causation: When an action directly leads to an outcome, such as a cause-effect relationship

ğŸ‘‰Static visualization: A data visualization that does not change over time unless it is edited

ğŸ‘‰Dynamic visualizations: Data visualizations that are interactive or change over time

ğŸ‘‰Tableau: A business intelligence and analytics platform that helps people visualize, understand,
and make decisions with data

ğŸ‘‰Data composition: The process of combining the individual parts in a visualization and
displaying them together as a whole

ğŸ‘‰Design thinking: A process used to solve complex problems in a user-centric way

ğŸ‘‰Headline: Text at the top of a visualization that communicates the data being presented

ğŸ‘‰Legend: A tool that identifies the meaning of various elements in a data visualization

ğŸ‘‰Subtitle: Text that supports a headline by adding context and description

ğŸ‘‰Alternative text: Text that provides an alternative to non-text content, such as images and
videos
